  "slug": "understanding-the-cn-ratio",
  "title": "Understanding the C:N ratio in composting",
  "subtitle": "Carbon, nitrogen, and why the balance determines whether your heap works",
  "excerpt": "The carbon-to-nitrogen ratio determines how fast compost breaks down and what gases it produces. The target for active decomposition is 25-30:1. Grass clippings sit at 20:1; cardboard at 400:1. Knowing the rough ratios of common materials lets you adjust any heap that is stalling, smelling, or overheating.",
  "type": "TECHNIQUE",
  "sourceNotes": "NRCS (US Natural Resources Conservation Service) C:N ratio tables for common compost materials. Cornell Composting resource, Ithaca NY. Rynk et al., On-Farm Composting Handbook (1992).",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Compost microorganisms need carbon for energy and nitrogen to build proteins. The",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "C:N ratio",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpba3b7400154ov4bwox1wne"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": "of the heap determines whether they can work efficiently. At the target 25-30:1, decomposition is fast, temperature builds, and neither carbon nor nitrogen is wasted. Outside that range, problems emerge: too much carbon slows the process (microorganisms run out of nitrogen); too much nitrogen produces ammonia (carbon runs out before nitrogen is incorporated).",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
